How can the risk of postnatal depression be reduced? (1/5) <NEWLINE>  <NEWLINE> A mum can put things into place which may reduce the risk of her suffering with post-natal depression. Having a support network can help with this.

The feelings of postnatal depression: (1/4) <NEWLINE>  <NEWLINE> If a mother has one easy birth, it doesn't mean that another will be easy. Likewise, if a mother has a difficult birth, it doesn't mean that their next will be difficult.

(3/3) <NEWLINE>  <NEWLINE> The mother may experience feelings of depression or anxiety as well as perhaps experiencing hallucinations. The mother may also have delusions about the baby, or delusions about possibly rejecting the baby.

What are potential risk factors? (1/3) <NEWLINE>  <NEWLINE> If there is a family history of depression, or an immediate family member has previously suffered with post-natal depression, this can potentially lead to the new mother suffering with the illness.

What are the symptoms? <NEWLINE>  <NEWLINE> - Confusion <NEWLINE> - Anxiety <NEWLINE> - Depression <NEWLINE>  <NEWLINE> Approximately 50% of women are afraid to let their health visitors know how they are feeling due to the fear of social services potentially taking their children away, or that they will be considered to be a bad mother.

At least 10% of mothers experience postnatal depression. This is often when the baby is 4-6 months old, however it can come through at any point in the first year. It can either come through gradually, or very quickly. There can be a range between mild to quite severe levels.

Baby Blues can be down to either alterations in levels of hormones after giving birth, or having experienced being in hospital. Usually, baby blues only lasts for 3-4 days, but it can go on for longer and become worse. If that's the case, it could become postnatal depression.
